                    <msContents>
                        <summary>This copy of the <title>Dīvān</title> by <persName>Ṣā’ib
                                Tabrīzī</persName> commences with his ghazals in alphabetical
                            order, and ends with a combination of isolated fragments. </summary>

                        <msItem xml:id="Persian_MS_862-item1">
                            <author key="person_91000370" change="#ids-cleanup">
                                <persName xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc" type="supplied">Ṣā’ib</persName>
                                <persName xml:lang="fa">صائب</persName>
                            </author>
                            <title xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc" key="work_20690" change="#ids-cleanup"
                                >Dīvān</title>
                            <title xml:lang="fa" key="work_20690" change="#ids-cleanup"
                                >دیوان</title>
                            <incipit xml:lang="fa" type="basmala"><locus type="page" from="1" to="1"
                                    > صقحه‌ی ۱ (page 1):</locus> اگر نه مدِّ بسم‌الله بودی تاجِ
                                عنوان‌ها * نگشتی تا قیامت نو خط شیرازه دیوان‌ها.</incipit>
                            <explicit xml:lang="fa">
                                <locus type="page" from="838" to="838"> صقحه‌ی ۸۳۸ (page
                                    838):</locus> چنان کز مرکز ثابت قدم پرگار می گردد * به قدر
                                پافشردن می دود گرد جهان معنی </explicit>
                            <colophon> No colophon.</colophon>
                            <textLang mainLang="fa">Persian</textLang>
                            <note>The conclusion appears to combine isolated fragments.</note>
                        </msItem>
                    </msContents>
                    <physDesc>
                        <objectDesc form="codex">
                            <supportDesc material="chart">
                                <support>Textblock of thin-weight, straight-grained, very fine
                                    externally sized and polished, cream-coloured
                                        <material>paper</material> probably handmade in the
                                        <placeName type="empire"
                                        ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7024418"
                                        key="place_7024418">Mughal Empire</placeName> with ~14 laid
                                    lines per cm and no discernible chain lines. First folio
                                    replaced, and following 7 remargined with comparatively evenly
                                    formed, thin-weight cross-grained ivory-coloured paper with ~9
                                    laid lines per cm and no discernible chain lines.</support>
                                <extent>
                                    <measure unit="page" quantity="840">840 pages, 8 flyleaves (ff.
                                        v + 420 + iii)</measure>. <dimensions type="leaf" unit="mm">
                                        <height>220</height>
                                        <width>123</width>
                                    </dimensions>
                                    <dimensions type="written" unit="mm">
                                        <height>166</height>
                                        <width>78</width>
                                    </dimensions>
                                </extent>
                                <foliation xml:id="modern">Paginated in pencilled Arabic numerals by
                                    former owner <persName type="standard"
                                        ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/66617580/" key="person_66617580"
                                        role="fmo ins" change="#role-assignment">Duncan
                                        Forbes</persName> followed in this record.</foliation>
                                <collation> Undetermined. <catchwords>Catchwords throughout most of
                                        the lower-left corners of the b
                                    sides.</catchwords></collation>


                                <condition>Handle text with caution. In fair condition, with many
                                    breaks in the marginal ruling, extensive water and insect damage
                                    and resulting discolouration on the margins, and historical
                                    repairs throughout, especially in the gutters.</condition>
                            </supportDesc>
                            <layoutDesc>
                                <layout columns="2" ruledLines="12" n="mistara"> Written in 2
                                    columns with 12 lines in the centres, with occasional obliquely
                                    written passages. Ruled with a <hi rend="italic">misṭarah</hi>
                                    hand guide.</layout>
                            </layoutDesc>

                        </objectDesc>
                        <handDesc>
                            <handNote scope="major" script="nasta_liq" medium="ink"> Written in
                                hasty but clear <material>black</material> nasta‘līq hand with
                                    <material>red</material> subheaders.</handNote>
                        </handDesc>
                        <decoDesc>
                            <decoNote type="headpiece"><label>Illumination:</label> Folio <locus
                                    from="1b" to="1b">1b</locus> bears gold cartouche bearing a
                                basmalla surmounted by a scalloped domed headpiece, with a gilt
                                ground, central palemtte designs, infilled and surmounted by further
                                gilt floral scrollwork, surrounded by gilt marginal ruling with
                                fishscale designs and green zig-zags.<lb/>
                                <dimensions type="Headpiece" unit="mm">
                                    <height>101</height>
                                    <width>86</width>
                                </dimensions></decoNote>
                            <decoNote type="marginal"><label>Ruling:</label> Text margins ruled in
                                    <material>gold</material> outlined with thin single internal and
                                double external black lines surrounded by single blue
                                lines.</decoNote>
                        </decoDesc>
                        <additions>
                            <lb/>
                            <label>Marginalia:</label> Notes in various hands of former owners
                            including Keene and Forbes, some of which indicate the
                                metres.<lb/><label>Inscriptions:</label> The <locus
                                from="Inner_front_cover" to="Inner_front_cover">right
                                pastedown</locus> numbered <q xml:lang="en">D. F. 29</q> and priced
                                <q xml:lang="en">£4.14.6</q> in pencil at bottom, both pertaining to
                            former owner <persName type="standard"
                                ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/66617580/" key="person_66617580"
                                role="fmo ins" change="#role-assignment">Duncan Forbes</persName>' catalogue.<lb/>
                            <label>Bookplates and pasted items:</label> The <locus
                                from="Inner_front_cover" to="Inner_front_cover">right
                                pastedown</locus> bears a pasted catalogue entry cut from <persName
                                role="bsl" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/person_128183577"
                                key="person_128183577">William Baynes and Son</persName>:<lb/>
                            <q xml:lang="en">231 DEEVANI Sayib- The Odes of Saeeb; 8vo splendidly
                                bound in crimson morocco, pp. 804-. A beautiful MS., most elegantly
                                written, the text inlaid in modern beautiful 6<hi rend="italic"
                                    >l</hi> 6<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.</q><lb/> The <locus
                                from="Inner_back_cover" to="Inner_back_cover">left pastedown</locus>
                            bears <q xml:lang="en">Bibliotheca Lindesiana</q> bookplate with
                            pencilled shelfmark the <q xml:lang="en">1/I</q> and an early
                            Bibliotheca Lindesiana label:<lb/>
                            <q xml:lang="en">Persian MSS No. <hi rend="strikethrough">68</hi></q>,
                            with the number crossed out and <q xml:lang="en">851</q> written aside. </additions>


                        <bindingDesc>
                            <binding calendar="#Gregorian" notBefore="1800" notAfter="1835">
                                <!-- Copied and pasted from another record. Update decoration. -->
                                <p>
                                    <persName role="fmo" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/79253656"
                                        key="person_79253656">J. B. B. Clarke</persName> describes
                                    the present binding, hence necessarily rebound before <date
                                        calendar="#Gregorian" when="1835">1835</date>. While it
                                    lacks his binder's ticket, the style closely comports with
                                    others volumes bound by the <placeName type="city"
                                        ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7011781"
                                        >London</placeName> firm of <persName type="standard"
                                        cert="high" role="bnd" key="person_17145938">Charles Lewis
                                        (1786-1836)</persName>.</p>
                                <p>Leather jointed endpapers prepared of yellow wove paper
                                    stiff-leaved with bright blue coated upper flyleaves added to
                                    the beginning and end. Resewn on on four recessed
                                        <material>cords</material> laced into the
                                        <material>pasteboards</material>. Edges trimmed and gilded,
                                    then decorative front-bead endbands worked in dark blue
                                        <material>silk</material> threads at <locus from="Head"
                                        to="Head">head</locus> and <locus from="Tail" to="Tail"
                                        >tail</locus>. Bound in full crimson straight-grained
                                    Morocco goatskin <material>leather</material> hollow-backed,
                                    over two false bands on the <locus from="Spine" to="Spine"
                                        >spine</locus>, tight jointed, and with wide turn-ins.</p>
                                <decoNote type="binding">Boards elegantly gold-tooled with
                                    <!-- five open
                                    cruciform designs with central florets and dots on the arms,
                                    surrounded by single fillet diamonds with solid dots at the
                                    joins, all connected with the same fillet lines which also
                                    surround the octagons. The central decoration connects to an
                                    inner margin with--> foliate
                                    scrollwork cornerpieces and stylized trefoils at the joins (the
                                    latter also seen on <idno>Persian MS 27</idno>). All bounded by
                                    exterior margins of single and double fillet lines with stylized
                                    trefoils at the joins. Board edges beard double fillets, while
                                    the interior dentelled bear palmette fleurons in the corners,
                                    connected pairs of single thin fillet lines joined at the
                                    leaves, with single lines also connecteding the bases, with dots
                                    on the joins. <locus from="Spine" to="Spine">Spine</locus>
                                    panels bear mitred triple pallet rectangles, with the triple
                                    single lines terminating in bold auricular palmettes. Titled:<lb/>
                                    <q xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc">DEEVAN I<lb/>SAHEEB</q>.</decoNote>
                                <p><dimensions type="binding" unit="mm">
                                        <height>231</height>
                                        <width>138</width>
                                        <depth>51</depth>
                                    </dimensions></p>
                                <condition>Handle binding with caution. In fair but stable
                                    condition, with extensive wear to the exterior joints and board
                                    edges.</condition>
                            </binding>
                        </bindingDesc>
                    </physDesc>
                    <history>
                        <origin change="#fix-dates">Probably completed in the <placeName
                                ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7000208" key="place_7000208"
                                >Indian subcontinent</placeName> undated, but possibly <origDate
                                cert="medium" calendar="#Gregorian" notBefore="1650" notAfter="1750"
                                >late 17th to early 18th century CE</origDate>.</origin>
                        <provenance><p>Acquired <persName role="ato ins fmo"
                                    ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/79255120" key="person_79255120">Henry
                                    George Keene (1781-1864)</persName>, who impressed his
                                Anglo-Persian seal and autograph on <locus from="1a" to="1a"
                                    >la</locus> dated <date calendar="#Gregorian" when="1802-10"
                                    >1802</date>.</p></provenance>
                        <provenance><p>Brought to <placeName
                                    ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7011781"
                                    key="place_7011781">London</placeName> by Keene while on
                                furlough, and sold to Methodist minister <persName role="fmo ins"
                                    key="person_120696480" ref="https://viaf.org/viaf/120696480/"
                                    >Rev. Adam Clarke (1762–1832)</persName>, as per his note dated
                                    <date>1803</date>. After his death, his son <persName role="fmo"
                                    key="person_79253656" ref="https://viaf.org/viaf/79253656/">J.
                                    B. B. Clarke (d. 1855)</persName> inherited the volume and
                                describes its present state in a catalogue published in <date
                                    calendar="#Gregorian" when="1835">1835</date>, p. 149, no.
                                69.</p></provenance>
                        <provenance><p>The next year on <date calendar="#Gregorian"
                                    when="1836-06-20">20 June 1836</date>, Clarke's son auctioned
                                his father's collection through the <placeName
                                    ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7011781"
                                    key="place_7011781">London</placeName> firm of <persName
                                    role="auc" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/133731879"
                                    key="person_133731879">Sotheby &amp; Son</persName> where
                                bookseller <persName role="bsl"
                                    ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/person_12230379" key="person_12230379"
                                    >John Cochran</persName> purchased it for £1 13
                            shillings.</p></provenance>
                        <provenance><p>Probably sold by Cochran to bookseller <persName role="bsl"
                                    ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/person_128183577"
                                    key="person_128183577">William Baynes and Son</persName> who
                                advertise it in their catalogue for £4 13 shillings that same year,
                                with the same entry pasted on the <locus from="Inner_back_cover"
                                    to="Inner_back_cover">left doublure</locus>.</p></provenance>
                        <provenance>
                            <p>Probably sold by <persName role="bsl"
                                    ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/person_128183577"
                                    key="person_128183577">William Baynes and Son</persName> to
                                    <orgName>King's College</orgName> Professor of Oriental
                                Languages <persName type="standard"
                                    ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/66617580/" key="person_66617580"
                                    role="fmo" change="#role-assignment">Duncan Forbes
                                    (1798–1868)</persName>. Forbes later described the volume in his
                                    <date calendar="#Gregorian" when="1866">1866</date> catalogue,
                                valued at £6 16<hi rend="italic">s</hi> 6<hi rend="italic">d</hi>,
                                before he sold his manuscript collection to his publisher <orgName
                                    role="bsl" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/152259747"
                                    key="person_152259747"><persName
                                        key="person_45159035185601380002" role="bsl"
                                        change="#prov-markup">W. H. Allen </persName>&amp;
                                    Co.</orgName> in exchange for an annuity. Subsequently sold by
                                that firm to <persName type="standard"
                                    ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/97751058/" key="person_97751058"
                                    role="fmo" change="#role-assignment">Alexander Lindsay, 25th
                                    Earl of Crawford (1812–1880)</persName> in <date
                                    calendar="#Gregorian" when="1866">1866</date>
                            </p>
                        </provenance>
                        <provenance><p>Purchased by <persName role="dnr" key="person_f6379"
                                    change="#prov-markup">Enriqueta Rylands (1843–1908)</persName>
                                in <date calendar="#Gregorian" when="1901">1901</date> from
                                    <persName role="fmo" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/9985420/"
                                    key="person_9985420">James Ludovic Lindsay, 26th Earl of
                                    Crawford (1847–1913)</persName>.</p></provenance>
                        <acquisition>
                            <p>Bequeathed by <persName key="person_f6379" change="#prov-markup"
                                    >Enriqueta Rylands (1843–1908)</persName> in <date
                                    calendar="#Gregorian" when="1908">1908</date> to the <orgName
                                    type="corporation" role="rps"
                                    ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/312795145/">John Rylands
                                    Library</orgName>, <placeName
                                    ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7010477"
                                    key="place_7010477">Manchester</placeName>.</p>
                        </acquisition>
                    </history>
